{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.77,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92627"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2547"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44584"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner complaining of raised, red bumps on both of her shins. These first appeared only two days prior and she has never had anything like this before. On further questioning, she complains of feeling generally lethargic and run down for the past six months, as well as occasionally becoming short of breath on exertion. She has no other rashes and is on no regular medications with no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there are multiple painful, erythematous, subcutaneous nodules on both shins, ranging from 1-3cm each. Other examinations are unremarkable. Routine blood results from six months ago are unremarkable aside from a corrected serum calcium of 2.90 mmol/L (2.10\u20132.60).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray and CT scan are performed, with one of the CT images shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amyloidosis","Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","Sarcoidosis","Tuberculosis","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is that of sarcoidosis. The reason for the chest X-ray and the CT chest is to look for evidence of pulmonary disease. The CT demonstrates bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy. The CT scan also shows some honeycombing and ground-glass opacity, with areas of bronchiectasis, which is most consistent with interstitial lung disease. The clinical picture of respiratory symptoms, systemic lethargy and malaise, combined with the description of what is likely erythema nodosum, is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This is further supported by the laboratory finding of hypercalcaemia, and the CT findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic pulmonary fibrosis \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Egranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E are causes of interstitial lung disease but do not explain the hypercalcaemia or erythema nodosum that are classically seen with sarcoidosis. \u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a granulomatous disease that may cause erythema nodosum and hilar lymphadenopathy but is less likely to account for hypercalcaemia in this case. \u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is also a multisystem disease that can affect the lung parenchyma, however, the radiographical appearance is usually that of nodular lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESarcoidosis is a multisystem disease, most commonly affecting the lungs and the intrathoracic lymph nodes (in 90% of patients with sarcoidosis). It is a disease characterised by non-caseating granulomas which is thought to have both genetic and environmental aetiologies. The average age at diagnosis is 35-50 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of sarcoidosis is variable ranging from asymptomatic (~50% of patients) to localised respiratory symptoms such as cough, dyspnoea and chest tightness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest radiograph of a patient with sarcoidosis can be staged using the following system:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage I: Mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy without infiltrates\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage II: Mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy with pulmonary infiltrates\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage III: Pulmonary infiltrates without adenopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage VI: Pulmonary fibrosis with volume loss and no adenopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe overall prognosis for early pulmonary sarcoidosis is good, with spontaneous regression in 80% of patients with stage I disease. However, more advanced stages have a less favourable prognosis with spontaneous regression seen in 1/3 of patients with stage II and III disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost patients with pulmonary sarcoidosis do not require treatment, and systemic therapy is only required for patients with progressive symptomatic disease, persistent infiltrates and progressive functional decline. Systemic glucocorticoids are first-line therapy for pulmonary sarcoidosis with the use of a steroid-sparing DMARD (disease-modifying antirheumatic drug) such as methotrexate. Biologic agents may also be indicated, with tumour necrosis alpha inhibitor, infliximab the biologic with the most robust evidence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary sarcoidosis alone does not usually require any treatment.","Sarcoidosis is a multisystem disease characterised by non-caseating granulomas, often affecting the lungs and intrathoracic lymph nodes."],"references":["Ungprasert P, Ryu JH, Matteson EL. Clinical Manifestations, Diagnosis, and Treatment of Sarcoidosis. Mayo Clin Proc Innov Qual Outcomes. 2019 Aug 2;3(3):358-375. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocpiqo.2019.04.006. PMID: 31485575; PMCID: PMC6713839. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31485575/","Belperio JA, Shaikh F, Abtin FG, Fishbein MC, Weigt SS, Saggar R, Lynch JP 3rd. Diagnosis and Treatment of Pulmonary Sarcoidosis: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Mar 1;327(9):856-867. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.1570. PMID: 35230389. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35230389/","Spagnolo P, Rossi G, Trisolini R, Sverzellati N, Baughman RP, Wells AU. Pulmonary sarcoidosis. Lancet Respir Med. 2018 May;6(5):389-402. doi: 10.1016/S2213-2600(18)30064-X. Epub 2018 Apr 3. PMID: 29625772. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29625772/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92627"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18674"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18674"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3f7890d4-9f86-4986-8a1e-67317804f831.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3f7890d4-9f86-4986-8a1e-67317804f831.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":551,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92627"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T09:25:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T09:26:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2473"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emed